---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';

const baseUrl = 'https://icontree.cosmoscope.workers.dev';

const promptText = `IconTree Icon Integration Prompt
Task: Integrate IconTree Icons Into Existing App
Objective
Add IconTree-powered Lottie icons to an existing app screen/feature. This is an INTEGRATION task,
not a new-product task.
Target
App/Framework: [FILL IN — e.g. React + Vite, Flutter, React Native, plain HTML/JS]
Screen or component being modified: [FILL IN — e.g. "Sidebar nav", "Settings screen"]
Existing Lottie library already in use (if any): [FILL IN, e.g. lottie-react, lottie-web, lottie_flutter, lottie-react-native]
Format Note
IconTree only serves Lottie animation JSON — there is no SVG format available from this source.
Do not write SVG-loading, SVG-parsing, or SVG-fallback code for these icons. Every icon, in both
modes below, is a .json file passed to the platform's Lottie player component.
Hard Constraints — Do NOT
Do NOT build a new icon library, browser, or gallery UI.
Do NOT build an icon marketplace or catalog page.
Do NOT recreate or clone IconTree's own search UI/backend.
Do NOT invent API fields, endpoints, or response properties beyond what's specified below.
Do NOT introduce a new design system, new color tokens, or new layout patterns — reuse what
the app already has (spacing, sizing, theme colors, component conventions).
Do NOT add a search UI if the request is manual/local mode.
Do NOT make network calls if the request is manual/local mode.
Do NOT write SVG handling code of any kind — IconTree is Lottie-JSON only.
Do NOT output unrelated boilerplate (no new app scaffold, no README, no unrelated files) —
only the code needed for this specific feature.
IconTree Reference
Base URL: ${baseUrl}
Mode 1 — AI-assisted icon selection (design-time only, NOT shipped in the app)
Use this mode yourself, as the coding assistant, to find and choose the right icon(s) before writing
app code. The app itself must NEVER call /icon/search at runtime — this is not a feature to build,
it's a lookup you perform once, offline, while authoring the code.
Endpoint: GET /icon/search
Query params (only these — no others):
q — search term (string)
category — category filter (string, optional)
page — page number (integer, optional)
pageSize — results per page (integer, optional)
Response shape (assume only these fields exist):
Selection workflow:
1. Call GET ${baseUrl}/icon/search?q=...&category=...&page=...&pageSize=...
2. Read response.results[] , pick the appropriate icon(s)
3. Build full URL: ${baseUrl}{result.url}
4. Fetch that URL to get the Lottie JSON animation data
5. Save the JSON as a local asset in the app (per Mode 2's file location) and write the final
integration using Mode 2 — static import, no network call in the shipped app
If the user explicitly wants a live, in-app icon search/picker (not just AI-assisted selection at build
time), stop and confirm that requirement separately — it is out of scope for a normal integration
and conflicts with the "Do NOT build a search UI" constraint above.
Mode 2 — Manual mode (pre-downloaded local JSON)
Use when the specific icon .json files have already been chosen/downloaded and bundled into the
app (including icons selected via Mode 1 above).
Assume files already exist locally at: [FILL IN — e.g. src/assets/icons/ , assets/lottie/ , public/icons/ ]
Load them the standard way for the platform (import, require, asset bundle reference, etc. —
whichever is idiomatic for the stack above)
Pass the loaded JSON into the platform's Lottie player component
No network requests, no search params, no dynamic fetching
Icon Color / Theming
IconTree icons ship with a fixed fill color baked into the Lottie JSON (often white or black) — this
is NOT guaranteed to match the app's theme.
Do NOT assume the source color is usable as-is in both light and dark themes.
Recolor the icon to match the app's existing icon/theme token, using whichever mechanism is
idiomatic for the platform's Lottie player (e.g. runtime color callbacks/dynamic properties,
colorFilters, or a JSON preprocessing step that swaps fill/stroke color values before passing to
the player).
The resulting color must respond to the app's current theme (light/dark or custom), not be
hardcoded to the source JSON's color.
Implementation Requirements
1. Match the existing component structure and naming conventions already used in the app.
2. Reuse existing styling (className/theme/tokens) — do not hardcode new colors, spacing, or
sizes unless the current design system requires a new token for this feature.
3. Icon size, loop, autoplay, and other Lottie player props should be configurable via
props/parameters, not hardcoded, unless the app's convention is to hardcode such values
{
"results": [
{ "url": "/relative/path/to/icon.json", "...other fields may exist but are NOT to be relied on unless explicitly requested": true }
]
}
elsewhere.
4. Handle loading and error states appropriately for AI-assisted fetch-at-authoring-time issues
(e.g. fetch failure, empty results during selection) — this does not apply to the shipped app in
manual mode.
5. Manual mode (the shipped code) requires no loading/error state beyond standard asset-not-
found handling, since data is local and bundled.
6. Code must be directly droppable into the existing codebase — assume it will be pasted into the
file(s) indicated in "Target" above.
Output Format
Return only the code required for this feature (component(s)/function(s) needed).
No extra scaffolding, no unrelated files, no explanatory essay — a short comment above non-
obvious logic is fine.
The final shipped code should reflect Mode 2 (local, static, themed) even if Mode 1 was used to
select the icons.
Production-ready: proper typing (if the stack uses TypeScript/Dart typing), no placeholder
TODOs left unresolved, no console.log debugging left in.`;
---

<Layout title="IconTree - AI Prompt">
  <div class="doc-content doc-content-wide prompt-shell">
    <div class="doc-nav">
      <a href="/" class="back-link">&lt; Back</a>
    </div>

    <section class="doc-hero">
      <span class="doc-kicker">AI Prompt</span>
      <h1>One Prompt to Use IconTree</h1>
      <p class="doc-lead">
        This prompt is for adding IconTree icons into an existing app, not for building a new icon library.
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="prompt-card">
      <h3>Prompt</h3>
      <p>Copy this prompt into your AI tool when you want it to build or integrate IconTree correctly.</p>
      <pre><code>{promptText}</code></pre>
    </section>

    <section class="lang-grid" aria-label="Prompt guidance">
      <article class="lang-card">
        <h3>Structure</h3>
        <p>
          The prompt tells the AI three things clearly: use the existing app, choose API or manual mode, and only
          write integration code for that app feature.
        </p>
      </article>

      <article class="lang-card">
        <h3>How to Add It</h3>
        <p>
          Paste the prompt first, then add one short line about your stack and target screen, like “Use React on the
          settings page” or “Use Android Kotlin in the onboarding screen”.
        </p>
      </article>
    </section>

    <section class="doc-callout">
      <p><strong>Example add-on lines</strong></p>
      <ul class="prompt-list">
        <li><code>Use React and Tailwind.</code></li>
        <li><code>Use Android Kotlin with a LottieAnimationView.</code></li>
        <li><code>Use manual local JSON files, not remote API calls.</code></li>
      </ul>
    </section>
  </div>

  <script>
    (function() {
      const preBlocks = Array.from(document.querySelectorAll('.doc-content pre')) as HTMLElement[];

      preBlocks.forEach((pre: HTMLElement) => {
        const btn = document.createElement('button');
        btn.className = 'copy-snippet-btn';
        btn.textContent = 'Copy';
        btn.type = 'button';
        pre.style.position = 'relative';
        pre.appendChild(btn);

        btn.addEventListener('click', () => {
          const code = pre.querySelector('code');
          const text = code?.textContent || '';

          navigator.clipboard.writeText(text).then(() => {
            btn.textContent = 'Copied!';
            btn.classList.add('copied');

            setTimeout(() => {
              btn.textContent = 'Copy';
              btn.classList.remove('copied');
            }, 2000);
          });
        });
      });
    })();
  </script>
</Layout>
